Well it all depends how you handle `null` at the boundary between the two languages. In Ceylon, we let you write either:<p><pre><code>    String str = javaObject.javaMethod();
</code></pre>
or:<p><pre><code>    String? str = javaObject.javaMethod();
 </code></pre>
In the first case, we insert a runtime type check that throws an `AssertionError` if `javaMethod()` returns `null`. In the second case we don&#x27;t.<p>That is to say, the Ceylon compiler recognizes that it&#x27;s dealing with a Java library where information about null is simply missing from the method signature and adjusts accordingly.
